{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a55b6472-703a-4cb1-bdf7-c59113e0c687","content":"## What's happening\n\n.NET has been **raising x86-64 baseline CPU requirements** across major versions. The error means your 2012-era hardware lacks instruction sets that .NET 11 now assumes are always available.\n\n**The x86-64 microarchitecture levels:**\n\n| Level | Key instructions added | Earliest CPUs |\n|-------|----------------------|---------------|\n| **v1** | Original AMD64 | ~2003 |\n| **v2** | SSE4.2, POPCNT, SSSE3 | ~2008–2009 (Nehalem/Westmere) |\n| **v3** | AVX2, BMI1/2, FMA | **2013 (Haswell)** |\n| **v4** | AVX-512 | ~2017 |\n\n.NET 9 raised the Linux x86-64 baseline to **v2** (which your .NET 10 nodes already met). .NET 11 likely raised it to **v3**, requiring **AVX2** — an instruction set your **pre-2013 hardware doesn't support**.\n\n## Why your other targets are fine\n\n- **Windows Arm64 (SQ1):** Separate Arm64 baseline; unaffected by x86 changes.\n- **Raspberry Pi 4 (Cortex-A72):** ARMv8-A, meets .NET's Arm64 baseline.\n\n## What you can do\n\n1. **Retire pre-Haswell hardware** — the simplest fix; anything from 2013+ should have AVX2.\n2. **Check your CPUs:** `lscpu | grep -i 'avx2\\|model name'` on the failing nodes.\n3. **If you can't replace hardware**, you may be able to build the runtime from source targeting v2, but this is unsupported and not recommended for production.\n\nThe root cause is that your 2012-era x86 nodes predate Intel Haswell (2013), which was the first to ship AVX2.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"01ce32f5-c25c-48b6-ba9c-9bb54de2b956","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets. This is a known issue with .NET's evolving hardware requirements. Let me explain what's happening.\n\nStarting with .NET 9 (and continuing in later versions), Microsoft raised the baseline CPU requirements for x86-64 on Linux. Specifically, .NET began requiring the **x86-64-v2** microarchitecture level, which includes instructions like SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT.\n\nHardware from 2012 might predate some of these requirements. For example, some older AMD CPUs or very early Intel Sandy Bridge processors might not support all x86-64-v2 instructions.\n\n\nThe shift happened between .NET 8 and .NET 9 — the earlier version only required the baseline x86-64-v1 instruction set, but .NET 9 tightened this to x86-64-v2 on Linux. Your 2012-era hardware, likely Sandy Bridge or Ivy Bridge generation, probably lacks some of the required instructions like CMPXCHG16B, LAHF/SAHF in 64-bit mode, or POPCNT. SAHF is the last instruction in that baseline. But if they're already running .NET 10 successfully, the x86-64-v2 requirements would already be enforced, so .NET 11 shouldn't suddenly break things unless Microsoft raised the baseline further—maybe to v3, which would require AVX and AVX2 support that older processors like Phenom II or Core 2 Duo wouldn't have. AVX2 support. Given that .NET 9 already moved to x86-64-v2, it's plausible .NET 11 bumped the baseline further to v3, which would explain why older hardware from 2012 that lacks AVX2 can no longer run the newer runtime.\n\nFor the ARM64 side, I'm checking whether the Surface Pro X with its SQ1 processor has the necessary instruction set support.  The Raspberry Pi 4 with its Cortex-A72 should handle .NET's ARM64 baseline without issues. The real problem here is specifically with older x86-64 CPUs that don't meet the newer baseline requirements. Since .NET 11 is beyond my training data, I should frame this around the known error message and baseline evolution pattern rather than making definitive claims about what a future version requires.","outputTokens":2036,"requestId":"B819:1F50C6:17F53C0:1AEE170:69FD3FC4"},"id":"c07e87f0-7776-4206-8402-873dd1fd1340","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:44:15.692Z","parentId":"ff235cd6-e150-40e5-9472-815da25cbcd7"}
